      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thomas L. Friedman says (column, July 3) that the United States should be "slowly intensifying oil conservation measures" in response to events in Saudi Arabia. But Congress has been doing the reverse by cutting the Department of Energy's conservation investments.</p>
        <p>Since 1991, a bipartisan effort has led to increased Federal funds for developing fuel-efficient vehicles as well as ones that run on fuels other than petroleum, like natural gas, electricity and renewable biofuels.</p>
        <p>Last year Congress slashed funds for these programs by one-third, and last month the House voted to cut the President's request for energy efficiency and advanced transportation technologies by 30 percent.</p>
        <p>As Mr. Friedman notes, we can "make ourselves less vulnerable to changes in that desert kingdom." Congress thus far seems to be missing the opportunity to do just that.</p>
        <p>CHRISTINE ERVIN Asst. Secy. for Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy Department of Energy Washington, July 8, 1996</p>
      </block>
